Our passivity is met with confusion among the other opposition parties. Sarath Muttetuwegama (CPSL) followed the arguing with a thorough condemnation of the motion and its lack of legality and precedent. He would leave the building like the TULF MP's

What followed was nothing short of comical. UNP MP's essentially ran unopposed in their proceedings most of them didnot speak, backbenchers were able to speak their mind freely. They began advocating ideas for how to "punish" Amirthalingam and other "traitorous" TULF MP's. Wippings, mutilations, drowning in the Beira and execution on Galle Face green were some of the methods discussed. 3 methods were so ghastly that they were immedietly expunged by the speaker.

CWC MP Saumiyamoorthy Thondaman gave a few words heavily critcising the motion. He went as far to claim that if the motion is passed, it would drive Tamils towards the militants.

Voting finally came, Thondaman abstained, members of the SLFP voted against. We were joined by one lone UNP'er' who voted against. He was Shelton Ranaraja from Senkadagala, a former SLFP member and notably also voted against deprivng Mrs Bandaranaike's civil rights last year.

The motion passed but as expected, nothing happened and A. Amirthalingam is still leader of the opposition. The motion has led to condemnations of the UNP from nearlly every other political outfit in the nation, their support has fallen among tamils and peoples confidence in the government is lowered. While we still voted against the motion, our lack of any coherent opposition in the debate and our unwillingness to join the CPSL and TULF walkout has lowered relations with the two.

